If you do that, try to adopt two or three, especially from a cat rescue organization that has taken the trouble to evaluate them for their ability to get along with people and other pets. They will socialize, especially with your help & encouragement. Play with them all together at once. Feed them together, interact with them in the same room. It's a bit of a time investment at first, but after three to six months everything should calm down to routine. They will keep each other company while you are out. DO NOT DECLAW THEM! Two solid scratching posts are a good idea. They leave scent with their paws where they scratch, so discourage anywhere else they scratch with diluted vinegar in water (1-2 teaspoons in a quart), damp wipe or spray on any surface they do try to scratch. It kills their scent mark and they look for a new place. Put "interesting things" near their scratching posts like toys, catnip, silvervine, a fresh pine branch, clean fresh water dish every morning and night, etc.

I get it that two or three cats is not an option for many people. It's just good for their mental health if you are able to. They will be slightly less dependent upon you to provide all of their socializing, thus a bit less annoying on occasion. Three is better than two because it's an unstable relationship. If only two, one often dominates and bullies the other. With three the dynamic shifts so one doesn't end up as the punching bag all the time.

I keep the main litterbox(es) next to the toilets in the house. Every time I visit the toilet is an opportunity to keep the litterbox neat so it's always an attractive option for them to use. Flush their poop with yours, use clumping litter for urine and keep a close-lidded bucket nearby to collect it. Flushing litter clumps in a toilet can clog it, so don't do that.
